Population SD is the square root of the population variance (sum of squares/N)

# first i am making a function for my calculations
pop_sd <- function(x) {sqrt(sum((x - mean(x))^2)/(length(x)))}

# using the function to find population SD for each random variable
psd.height <- pop_sd(zombie$height); psd.height
## [1] 4.30797
psd.weight <- pop_sd(zombie$weight); psd.weight
## [1] 18.39186
psd.age <- pop_sd(zombie$age); psd.age
## [1] 2.963583
psd.killed <- pop_sd(zombie$zombies_killed); psd.killed
## [1] 1.747551
psd.ed <- pop_sd(zombie$years_of_education); psd.ed
## [1] 1.675704

# loading this package so i can arrange ggplot graphs, it works like par(mfrow)

Question 3

Use {ggplot} to make scatterplots of height and weight in relation to age. Do these variables seem to be related? In what way?

# we use geom_point to make scatter plots with ggplot! 
height_age <- ggplot(data = zombie, aes(x = age, y = height)) + geom_point() +
              xlab("Age") + ylab("Height") + theme_bw() + geom_smooth(method= "lm")

weight_age <- ggplot(data = zombie, aes(x = age, y = weight)) + geom_point() +
              xlab("Age") + ylab("Weight") + theme_bw() + geom_smooth(method= "lm")

ggarrange(height_age, weight_age, ncol = 2, nrow = 1)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

These variables look related! It looks like height and weight both increase as age increases. However, there is greater spread for the points related to weight and age. Adding a line allowed me to see the difference in slope between the two graphs; the line helps explain how the points for weight x age are more spread out than the points for height x age.

Question 4

Using histograms and Q-Q plots, check whether the quantitative variables seem to be drawn from a normal distribution. Which seem to be and which do not (hint: not all are drawn from the normal distribution)? For those that are not normal, can you determine from which common distribution they are drawn?

Im first making histograms for each quantitative variable (height, weight, age, number zombies killed, and years of education)

par(mfrow = c(2, 3))
hist(zombie$height, main = "Height")
hist(zombie$weight, main = "Weight")
hist(zombie$age, main = "Age")
hist(zombie$zombies_killed, main = "Number of zombies killed") 
hist(zombie$years_of_education, main = "Years of education")

The histograms on the second row for numbers of zombies killed and years of education dont look normally distributed. Their distribution is skewed towards the left and has a long tail. The rest of the histograms on the first row for weight, height, and age look normally distributed (?). The one for weight has a slightly longer tail on the right but the associated qqplot (see below) looks normally distributed.

Next, Im assessing the same data using QQ plots

par(mfrow = c(2, 3))
qqnorm(zombie$height, main = "Height"); qqline(zombie$height)
qqnorm(zombie$weight, main = "Weight"); qqline(zombie$weight)
qqnorm(zombie$age, main = "Age"); qqline(zombie$age)
qqnorm(zombie$zombies_killed, main = "Number zombies killed"); qqline(zombie$zombies_killed)
qqnorm(zombie$years_of_education, main = "Years of education"); qqline(zombie$years_of_education)

Height, weight, and age look normally distributed according to these qqplots. The second row with number of zombies killed and years of education dont look normally distributed. The step ladder shape comes from the fact that data from these variables are discrete and rounded, but the points do not fall along x=y. This looks like a Poisson distribution.

Also estimate the standard error for each variable, and construct the 95% confidence interval for each mean. Note that for the variables that are not drawn from the normal distribution, you may need to base your estimate of the CIs on slightly different code than for the normal

Calculating sample mean, sample standard deviation, standard error of the mean, and 95% confidence interval for each mean for the same variables again, starting with HEIGHT:

# calculating mean
mean_height <- mean(zombie_subset$height); mean_height
## [1] 67.63939
# calculating SD, we can use the built-in function this time because we're drawing from a sample! 
sd_height <- sd(zombie_subset$height); mean_height
## [1] 67.63939
# calculating standard error of the mean using the equation: sd/sqrt(n)
sem_height <- sd_height/sqrt(length(zombie_subset$height)); sem_height
## [1] 0.6445838
# calculating 95% CIs with help from Module 9
lower_h <- mean_height - qnorm(1 - 0.05/2) * sem_height  # (1-alpha)/2 each in upper and lower tails of distribution
upper_h <- mean_height + qnorm(1 - 0.05/2) * sem_height  
ci_height <- c(lower_h, upper_h); ci_height
## [1] 66.37603 68.90275

Doing the same for WEIGHT:

Challenges Faced

  1. I was initially unable to use curl to load my dataset. I kept receiving an error message until I realized that I pasted the wrong link. I needed to paste the link to the raw data, not the link to githubs preview of the .csv file.
  2. Took me a while to look for equation for population SD, had to understand how it was different (mathematically) from sample SD and figure out how to turn it into a function that could be used for each variable
  3. Some of the qqplots for question 4 looked like stepladders instead of a straight line, which confused me. I found out that this pattern comes from using discrete, rounded values. This checks out when looking at the data for numbers of zombies killed and years of education. I can still interpret the qqplot despite this different look.
  4. I wasnt sure how to calculate the confidence intervals for the Poisson distributed variables (numbers of zombies killed and years of education). I did some googling and found this link. Im not sure if this is correct and would like to revisit this in class and see it done by hand.
  5. I couldnt figure out how to make a for loop to start off queston 6! I was able to create 100 random samples but I didnt know how to calculate the mean for each variable within the for loop. I didnt have enough time to figure this out so I used a different method.
